<BODY id="www-radionz-co-nz" class="news"><DIV id="pw"><DIV id="hw"><DIV id="head"><DIV id="topnav"><DIV id="crumbs"><P class="breadcrumbs"><A href="/">RNZ Home</A>»<A href="/news">News</A>»<A href="/news/regional">Regional</A>» Shellfish toxin warning for Bay of Plenty</P></DIV></DIV><DIV class="clear"> </DIV></DIV></DIV><DIV id="mw"><DIV id="wrapper"><DIV id="cont-pri"><DIV class="newsstory"><H2>Shellfish toxin warning for Bay of Plenty</H2><P class="posted">Updated at  7:07 pm on 16 January 2012</P><P><STRONG>The Waikato District Health Board has issued a warning about a potentially fatal shellfish toxin affecting the Bay of Plenty.</STRONG></P><P>Toxins that cause Paralytic Shellfish Poisoning (PSP) have reached warning levels along the coast from Tairua to the Whakatane Heads, Matakana and Motiti islands.</P><P>The board says bivalve shellfish, catseyes and kina should not be taken or eaten, while paua, crayfish and crabs should have the guts removed before cooking.</P><P>The DHB says in severe cases, PSP can cause paralysis and respiratory failure.</P><P>Monitoring of toxin levels will continue in the affected areas.</P><P class="copyright">Copyright © 2012, Radio New Zealand</P></DIV></DIV><DIV id="cont-sec"><DIV class="whaabout"><H3>Top Stories</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV></BODY></HTML>